# CadQuery Project Conventions

## Repository Layout

- Keep reusable model definitions in root `*.py` model files.
- Keep generic CLI utilities in `scripts/` (export/check helpers).
- Write generated outputs only to `exports/` (do not write exports to project root).
- Diagnostic renders go to `renders/` (not committed).
- Do not add model-specific scripts under `scripts/`; scripts must work from passed parameters.

## Model Interface Contract

- Every model module must define:
  - `PARAMS` (dict of default dimensions/options)
  - `MODEL_NAME` (stable model identifier string)
  - `build_model(p=PARAMS)` returning a dict with:
    - `name`: model name
    - `assembly`: CadQuery assembly (or `None`)
    - `parts`: non-empty dict mapping `part_name -> cadquery shape`
- Keep part naming stable (`body`, `base`, `lid`, `rear_cover`, etc.) to avoid downstream script breakage.
- Avoid script-specific assumptions inside model modules; scripts consume only the standard `build_model()` output.

## Modeling Rules

- Any printable part (`body`, `base`, `lid`) must be a single solid.
- Prefer overlapping geometry (not only touching faces) when uniting parts.
- For structural joins, add explicit bridges/ribs so boolean unions remain connected.
- Keep key dimensions in `PARAMS` and avoid hard-coded magic numbers in assembly placement.
- Build incrementally: start with the basic shell, verify, then add features one at a time. Verify after each addition.
- Add 0.05–0.1 mm overlap on cutting tools to ensure clean boolean cuts.

## LLM Modeling Guidance

- **Never trust LLM memory for hardware dimensions.** Always look up official mechanical drawings / datasheets (use WebFetch) before coding port positions, mounting holes, or connector sizes.
- **Spatial reasoning is error-prone.** Explicitly annotate coordinate systems: which axis points which direction, which face is front/back/top/bottom. ASCII diagrams in code comments help.
- **Common spatial mistakes:** features on the wrong face, protrusions pointing inward instead of outward, "near" vs "far" swapped. After writing geometry, render and cross-section to catch these.

## Validation Workflow

- After substantial geometry edits, always run:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/check_connectivity.py --model <module>`
  - Use `--verbose` for extended diagnostics (topology, bbox, volume, watertight).
- Before commits that touch model geometry or export logic, rerun the check.
- If multiple models are affected, run the check once per affected model.
- Only treat a model as valid when both conditions hold:
  - `solids == 1` for each printable part
  - `isValid == True`
- If the check fails, fix connectivity first; do not export or commit as final.
- **Visual inspection** — after validation passes, render and inspect:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/render_model.py --model <module>`
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/cross_section.py --model <module> --plane Z=<value>`
  - Check: features in correct positions, holes on correct faces, overall shape matches intent.
  - Cross-section at each major feature height to verify wall thickness and internal structure.

## Print-Readiness Checklist

Before delivering STL files, verify:
- BRepCheck valid, watertight (1 shell per solid).
- No thin walls (< 0.8 mm for FDM).
- Overhangs < 45° or supported.
- Screw holes have enough surrounding material.
- Tolerances added for mating parts (+0.2–0.3 mm per side).

## Export Workflow

- Use script entrypoints, not ad-hoc exporter commands:
  - `./.venv311/bin/python scripts/export_model.py --model <module>`
- Always run connectivity checks before export; never treat multi-solid output as acceptable.
- Keep export paths configurable via `--out` and default to `exports/`.
- Prefer script-level generic export logic driven by `build_model()` output; avoid per-model branching in scripts.

## Script CLI Consistency

- All scripts under `scripts/` share these conventions where applicable:
  - `--model <python_module_name>` identifies the model module to import.
  - `--params <json_path>` applies validated PARAMS overrides.
  - `--part <name>` operates on a single part.
- `check_connectivity.py` must not write CAD files; it is validation-only.
- `export_model.py` must write outputs only to the configured `--out` directory (default `exports/`).
- `render_model.py` and `cross_section.py` accept `--model` or `--file` for input, output to `--out` (default `renders/`).

## Git Hygiene

- Never commit virtual environments or generated CAD outputs.
- Keep `.gitignore` aligned with `.venv*`, `__pycache__`, `exports/`, and `renders/`.
